#: Game.Levels.Samarkand.L02_ImageMap
msgid "Intro Samarkand L02"
msgstr "Arapuka dictates another exercise."

#. §0: `apply congr_fun at h`
#. §1: `rw [← comp_apply (f:= f)]`
#. §2: `rw [← comp_apply]`
#. §3: `(f:=f)`
#. §4: `f`
#. §5: `comp_apply`
#: Game.Levels.Epo.L04_RightInverse
msgid ""
"Try §0 or §1.\n"
"§2 without §3 does not work. You must explicitly point out which value\n"
"the variable §4 should have in statment §5."
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: You could use §0 or §1. (§2 without §3 does not work here – "
"you must explicitly specify the value of the variable §4 when invoking §5."

#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L04_Boss_infinitely_many_primes
msgid "Conclusion Euklid L04"
msgstr ""
"Euclid is thrilled and dances around in circles. He doesn't want to let you "
"go. You promise to stay in touch."

#: Game.Levels.Prado.L06_Prime_Specialize__prime_def
msgid "Intro Prado L06"
msgstr ""
"**You**: Good. Can you show me how to work with prime numbers now? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Let me see if I have an exercise concerning prime numbers in "
"stock... This one, perhaps?"

#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L06_Summary
msgid "Intro Spinoza L06"
msgstr ""
"**You**: But couldn't we have proven the last statement just as easily by "
"contradiction? \n"
"\n"
"**Benedictus**: Sure. I just thought a second proof by contradiction would "
"be boring. But you are welcome to try the problem again. Here, I'll give it "
"to you to take with you on your journey. But now make sure you get going!"

#: Game.Levels.Saturn.L01_Rewrite_equality
msgid "Intro Saturn L01"
msgstr "Suddenly, you receive a radio message."

#. §0: `(g ∘ f) «{x}»`
#. §1: `g (f «{x}»)`
#. §2: `simp`
#: Game.Levels.Vieta.L06_Piecewise
msgid "Rewrite §0 to §1 via §2"
msgstr ""
"**You**: Ah, so now I can rewrite §0 to §1? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: §2 should do the trick."

#. §0: `constructor`
#. §1: `⊢ A ∧ B`
#. §2: `⊢ A`
#. §3: `⊢ B`
#. §4: `⊢ A ↔ B`
#. §5: `⊢ A → B`
#. §6: `⊢ B → A`
#. §7: `obtain`
#. §8: `A ∨ B`
#. §9: `left`
#. §10: `right`
#: Game.Doc.Tactic
msgid ""
"The §0 tactic breaks down a proof goal into its constituent parts:\n"
"\n"
"| before | after                |\n"
"|:------------ |:----------------------- |\n"
"| §1    | §2 and §3         |\n"
"| §4    | §5 and §6 |\n"
"\n"
"## Friends and relatives\n"
"\n"
"* You can break down an *assumption* into its components using §7.\n"
"* If you want to prove §8, you have to choose one side using §9 or §10."
msgstr ""
"The tactic §0 breaks down a proof goal into its constituent parts: \n"
"\n"
"| before | after | \n"
"|:------------ |:----------------------- |\n"
"| §1 | §2 and §3 | \n"
"| §4 | §5 and §6 | \n"
"\n"
"## Friends and relatives \n"
"\n"
"* You break down an *assumption* into its components using §7. \n"
"* If you want to prove §8, you must choose a side using §9 or §10."

#: Game.Levels.Piazza.L07_antisymm_iff
msgid "Intro Piazza L07"
msgstr "**Set**: And I like this equivalence."

#. §0: `«{f}»`
#. §1: `«{ha}»`
#: Game.Levels.Mono.L01_Injective
msgid "Use §0 to simplify assumption §1"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: I think you should now simplify assumption §1 using the "
"definition of §0."

#. §0: `rw [«{h}»]`
#. §1: `apply («{h}».mp)`
#. §2: `obtain ⟨mp, mpr⟩ := «{h}»`
#: Game.Levels.Implis.L11_Iff
msgid "Instead of §0 and §1 try §2"
msgstr ""
"**You**: Well, I know §0 and §1, but we wanted to avoid those this time. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: What you could do is split the assumption into two parts with "
"§2."

#: Game.Levels.Robotswana.L03
msgid "Conclusion Robotswana L03"
msgstr ""
"**You**: Now I'm curious who lost or threw away these notes. Come on, let's "
"move on."

#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L04_sum_subset
msgid "Intro Babylon L04"
msgstr ""
"You continue wandering from tower to tower. Finally, you stop at a tower "
"that seems strange to you. After walking around it once, you realise why: "
"there is no entrance. Eventually, you notice a floor slab with the following "
"inscription."

#. §0: `congr_arg`
#. §1: `x = y`
#. §2: `f x = f y`
#. §3: `apply congr_arg`
#: Game.Levels.Vieta.L08_CongrArg
msgid "Try §0. If §1, then §2 when using §3"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Oh, that calls for §0. If you already know §1, you get §2 with "
"§3."

#. §0: `preimage f`
#: Game.Levels.Samarkand.L08_Preimage_Injective
msgid "Explain surcetivity by §0"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: A mapping is surjective if and only if the induced mapping §0, "
"which maps a subset onto the preimage of this subset, is injective? Is that "
"correct? \n"
"\n"
"**You**: I believe so. I think I've seen that before. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Well then, let's do this!"

#. §0: `A ∨ B`
#. §1: `right`
#. §2: `left`
#: Game.Doc.Tactic
msgid ""
"If the proof target is of the form §0, you choose §1 to show the right "
"side.\n"
"\n"
"## Friends and relatives\n"
"\n"
"With §2, you choose the left side accordingly."
msgstr ""
"If the goal is of the form §0, §1 means that you will show the right side. \n"
"\n"
"## Friends and relatives \n"
"\n"
"Analogously, with §2 you decide for the left side."

#: Game.Levels.Samarkand.L05_InjectiveFibre
msgid "Conclusion Samarkand L05"
msgstr "Arapuka is still lying completely still, but she looks happy."

#. §0: `Function.RightInverse f g`
#. §1: `LeftInverse g f`
#. §2: `∀ x, g (f x) = x`
#. §3: `Function.RightInverse`
#. §4: `RightInverse`
#. §5: `RightInverse`
#: Game.Doc.Definition
msgid ""
"§0 is defined as §1.\n"
"In other words: §2.\n"
"\n"
"You have to write §3  instead of §4,\n"
"as §5 is ambigous in Leanic."
msgstr ""
"§0 is defined as §1. In plain language, this means §2, of course. "
"Unfortunately, you must write §3 instead of §4, as §5 is ambiguous in "
"Leanish."

#: Game.Levels.Implis.L02_Revert
msgid "Intro Implis L02"
msgstr ""
"The Head of Operations takes a stack of paper out of a container. \n"
"\n"
"**Head of operations**: Quite a lot has accumulated here. It would be really "
"great if you could help me a little more. \n"
"\n"
"He hands you the top sheet."

#. §0: `f «{A}»`
#: Game.Levels.Robotswana.L10_Characterize
msgid "Rewrite §0 as sum of basis elements"
msgstr "**You**: And now we write §0 as a sum of basis elements."

#. §0: `omega`
#: Game.Levels.Luna.L10_Icc_subset_Icc_iff
msgid "Intro Luna L10: Use §0 again"
msgstr ""
"**Ritha** (*to Lina*): Please, let me ask one more question... \n"
"\n"
"**Lina**: Okay, just one... But not about §0 again! \n"
"\n"
"Ritha's eyes widen and she looks at Lina imploringly. \n"
"\n"
"**Lina**: If you *absolutely* must. But be quick! We really don't have any "
"more time!"

#. §0: `«{b}»`
#. §1: `a`
#. §2: `intro`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L02_prod_insert
msgid ""
"Goal: if §0 divides factor §1 of a product then it also divides the "
"product.\n"
"Try §2"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: This line also looks very reasonable: if a number §0 divides a "
"factor §1 of a product, then it certainly also divides the entire product.\n"
"\n"
"**You**: But already the first line of the “proof” doesn't make any sense "
"whatsoever. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: No, it doesn't. But let's again try it ourselves. We'll start "
"with §2, of course."

#. §0: `obtain ⟨h₁, h₂⟩ := «{h}»`
#. §1: `\\<>`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L13_Or
msgid "Try §0. Write brackets as §1"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: You already know how to handle an 'and' in the assumptions: "
"§0. Remember you can write the angle brackets as §1."

#: Game.Levels.Prado.L04_99
msgid "Intro Prado L04"
msgstr ""
"Guino now seems a little irritated that you are taking so little interest in "
"his wonderful museum. He feels ignored. To get your attention, he gives you "
"the following problem."

#. §0: `(A : Prop)`
#. §1: `(True : Prop)`
#. §2: `(False : Prop)`
#: Game.Doc.Definition
msgid ""
"§0 is any statement, without further specification as to whether it is true, "
"false, or\n"
"unprovable.\n"
"\n"
"See also §1 and §2 for the unconditionally true and false\n"
"statements, respectively."
msgstr ""
"§0 is any statement, without further indication as to whether it is true, "
"false or unprovable. \n"
"\n"
"See also §1 and §2 for statements that are unconditionally true or false."

#. §0: `rw [hₓ]`
#. §1: `rw [← hₓ]`
#: Game.Levels.Saturn.L01_Rewrite_equality
msgid "Try if §0 and §1 can be used as in Implis"
msgstr ""
"**You**: So I can also use §0 and §1? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Why don't you try?"

#. §0: `¬`
#: Game.Levels.Quantus.L09_PushNeg
msgid "Remind about §0"
msgstr "**You**: I see. A §0 on the far left. What a surprise ..."

#. §0: `A × A`
#: Game.Levels.Cantor.L08_CantorDiag_IsFixedPt
msgid "Intro Cantor L08: Mapping defined on product §0 with diagonal"
msgstr ""
"Cantor lands, gets off his bike, returns to the edge of the stage and rubs "
"his hands together. \n"
"\n"
"**Cantor**: You're getting closer now! If you look carefully, you have a map "
"in front of you that is defined on a product §0! And the product has a "
"diagonal!"

#. §0: `f`
#. §1: ```
#. ∀ ⦃a b⦄, a < b → f a < f b
#. ```
#: Game.Doc.Definition
msgid ""
"A mapping §0 is strictly monotonous, if:\n"
"\n"
"§1"
msgstr ""
"A mapping §0 is strictly monotonic if the following holds: \n"
"\n"
"§1"

#. §0: `x ≠ y`
#. §1: `¬ x = y`
#. §2: `unfold Ne`
#: Game.Doc.Definition
msgid "Inequality §0 is defined as §1.  You can see this with §2."
msgstr "Inequality §0 is defined as §1. You can see this with §2."

#. §0: `by_contra g`
#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L06_Summary
msgid "This time start with §0"
msgstr ""
"Once you've managed to escape from the asteroid's gravitational field, you "
"return to the problem at hand. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Okay, so this time we'll start with §0!"

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L12_Or
msgid "Conclusion Logo L12"
msgstr "This formalosopher also leaves happily."

#: Game.Levels.Robotswana
msgid "Intro Robotswana"
msgstr ""
"You land on a warm planet and step out onto a vast grassy landscape. A few "
"trees here and there. After looking around for a while, Scribble discovers "
"tracks leading away from your landing site. You hesitate for a moment but "
"then decide to follow the tracks."

#. §0: `∃! a`
#. §1: `a`
#. §2: `use a`
#. §3: `simp`
#: Game.Levels.Samarkand.L05_InjectiveFibre
msgid "Try §0 to construct §1, Try §2 and §3"
msgstr ""
"**You**: For §0, I first construct the element §1 that I want to use... \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: ...and then you apply §2 and §3. Exactly."

#: Game.Levels.Quantus.L06_not_even_iff_odd
msgid "Intro Quantus L06"
msgstr ""
"The next page appears immediately. It seems as though they have agreed on a "
"compromise this time."

#. §0: `ext`
#: Game.Levels.Piazza.L06_Ext2__univ2
msgid "Conclusion Piazza L06: Explain that §0 means extensionality"
msgstr ""
"**You** *(to Scribble)*: Why is ext actually called ext? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: How should I know where the boy got his name from?\n"
"\n"
"**You**: No, I mean this §0 here! \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Oh, I see. Logicians refer to the principle that two sets are "
"equal if and only if they have the same elements as *extensionality*. I "
"guess the formalosophers shortened that to *ext*."

#. §0: `ext`
#: Game.Levels.Samarkand.L03_SurjectiveRange
msgid "Again show equality of sets by using §0"
msgstr "**Scribble**: Isn't this again an equality of sets? §0!"

#. §0: `apply sum_congr`
#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L03_sum_congr
msgid "try §0"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Exactly. Now you can write §0 – if two indexed sums have "
"identical index sets, and if the individual expressions being summed up are "
"also equal, then the sums themselves are equal."

#: Game.Levels.Vieta.L01_FunctionNotation
msgid "Intro Vieta L01"
msgstr ""
"**Vieta:** Listen, I'll show you something... He gives you a piece of paper."

#: Game.Levels.Piazza
msgid "Intro Piazza"
msgstr ""
"It appears that you have landed on a trading planet. There are merchants "
"everywhere offering their wares for sale. You eye a few stalls curiously. "
"Some things look familiar and edible, many do not. But everything is neatly "
"sorted. There are baskets of blueberries (?), crates of red vegetables that "
"remind you of tomatoes, open sacks of small pink stars, etc. \n"
"\n"
"A few children – or at least a few rather small formalosophers who behave "
"like children – almost run into your feet. Scribble jumps, and they notice "
"you and stop. They introduce themselves as “Fin”, “Ext”, “Mem”, “Set” and "
"”Sub”, and seem curious. \n"
"\n"
"**Fin**: What are you doing here? \n"
"\n"
"**You**: Um... just poking around a bit.\n"
"\n"
"**Set**: We're here to learn some set theory. Our parents dropped us off "
"here. \n"
"\n"
"**Ext**: For educational purposes, so to speak. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: So, have you learned anything yet?"

#. §0: `«{h}» : «{A}»`
#. §1: `suffices`
#. §2: `suffices k : B`
#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L03_ByContra
msgid "Apply contradiction with §0 via §1 with §2"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: So now you have an assumption §0, and you have to derive a "
"contradiction from it. \n"
"\n"
"For example, you could now use §1 to say which contradiction you would like "
"to derive, like so: §2."

#. §0: `lt_trichotomy`
#: Game.Levels.Mono.L06_StrictMono
msgid "Try case distinction. Use §0"
msgstr "**Scribble**: Now perhaps distinguish cases. Do you remember §0?"

#: Game.Levels.Iso
msgid "Iso"
msgstr "Iso"

#. §0: `if … then … else`
#. §1: `fun x ↦ if 0 ≤ x then x else -x`
#. §2: `h : A`
#. §3: `rw [if_pos h]`
#. §4: `if A then B else C`
#. §5: `B`
#. §6: `h : ¬ A`
#. §7: `rw [if_neg h]`
#. §8: `if A then B else C`
#. §9: `C`
#: Game.Doc.Tactic
msgid ""
"With §0, you can define mappings with two branches of definition.\n"
"\n"
"For example, §1 defines the absolute value function.\n"
"\n"
"## Friends and relatives\n"
"\n"
"* If you have §2 as an assumption, you can use\n"
"§3 to reduce the expression §4 to §5.\n"
"* If you have §6 as an assumption, you can use\n"
"§7 to reduce the expression §8 to §9."
msgstr ""
"With §0, you can define mappings with two branches. \n"
"\n"
"For example, §1 defines the absolute value function. \n"
"\n"
"## Friends and relatives \n"
"\n"
"* If you have §2 as an assumption, you can use §3 to reduce the expression "
"§4 to §5. \n"
"* If you have §6 as an assumption, you can use §7 to reduce the expression "
"§8 to §9 in the same way."

#: Game.Levels.Saturn.L05_Ring
msgid "Conclusion Saturn L05"
msgstr ""
"“Pass” says the anonymous radio operator succinctly. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: I think the engine has sufficiently regenerated by now. Let's "
"get out of here!"

#. §0: `a ∣ b`
#. §1: `∃ k, b = a * k`
#. §2: ```
#. rw [dvd_iff_exists_eq_mul_left] at *
#. ```
#: Game.Levels.Prado.L02_dvd_iff_exists_eq_mul_left
msgid ""
"§0 is defined as §1. State is explicitly with\n"
"§2\n"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: §0 is, of course, defined as §1. It's best to write this out "
"explicitly everywhere from the beginning:\n"
"§2.\n"
" \n"

#: Game.Levels.Babylon.L02_Card2
msgid "Intro Babylon L02"
msgstr "You go over to the next tower."

#. §0: `have h : P`
#. §1: `suffices h : P`
#: Game.Doc.Tactic
msgid ""
"With §0, you introduce an intermediate result.\n"
"You must then prove this intermediate result\n"
"before you can continue with the actual proof.\n"
"\n"
"## Friends and relatives\n"
"§1 works in exactly the same way, except that you can continue with the main "
"proof first and\n"
"only have to prove your intermediate result at the very end."
msgstr ""
"With §0, you introduce an intermediate result. You must then prove this "
"intermediate result before you can continue with the actual proof. \n"
"\n"
"## Friends and relatives \n"
"§1 works in exactly the same way, except that you can continue with the main "
"proof first and only have to prove your intermediate result at the very end."

#. §0: `1 «{i}» «{i}»`
#. §1: `1 • _`
#: Game.Levels.Robotswana.L05_EBasisDiagSum
msgid "Explain simplification of §0 and §1"
msgstr ""
"**You**: Thank you, that helps! This step should be easy: a sum over one "
"element, where §0 is one again, and §1 also simplifies!"

#. §0: `(«{A}» ∧ «{B}») ∨ «{A}»`
#. §1: `obtain …`
#. §2: `obtain ⟨h₁, h₂⟩ := «{h}»`
#. §3: `obtain h | h := «{h}»`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L13_Or
msgid ""
"Observe goal as §0.\n"
"Do not try §1 as §2 but as §3"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Look, when you touch an assumption with your finger, it "
"highlights how the brackets are set. Crazy...\n"
"\n"
"**You**: Ah, I see: §0! \n"
"\n"
"**You**: I'm beginning to have my suspicions regarding this whole circus: "
"first an “and” in the target, then “and” in the assumption, then “or” in the "
"target and now “or” in the assumption. They must have agreed on this in "
"advance!\n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: So what? Let’s not spoil their fun. We'll be done here in a "
"moment, and then we can fly on to a more interesting planet. \n"
"\n"
"**You**: So, §1 again? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Yes, but this time §3 rather than $2."

#. §0: `∧`
#. §1: `∨`
#. §2: `obtain ⟨h₁, h₂⟩ := h`
#. §3: `obtain h \\| h := h`
#. §4: `constructor`
#. §5: `left`
#. §6: `right`
#: Game.Levels.Logo.L14_Summary
msgid ""
"Intro Logo L14: The most important tactics of this chapter concerning §0 and "
"§1.\n"
"For both logical operations the tactis §2 and §3 can be used respectivelly.\n"
"Analogously, when working with the goal §4 and §5/§6 can be used "
"respectivelly as well."
msgstr ""
"The last subject steps forward. Her request is somewhat more complicated "
"than the previous ones. \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Just throw everything at it that you've learned. Here, I'll "
"try to be helpful by showing you the four most important tactics for this "
"situation again. \n"
"\n"
"| (Overview) | And (§0) | Or (§1) | \n"
"|:------------|:-------------------------|:------------------------| \n"
"| Assumption | §2 | §3 | \n"
"| Goal | §4 | §5/§6 | "

#. §0: `f`
#. §1: `A`
#. §2: `A`
#. §3: `A`
#. §4: `f`
#: Game.Levels.Cantor.L01_CantorPowerset
msgid ""
"Intro Cantor L01: Mapping §0 from §1 to the power set of §2, and the set\n"
"of all elements in §3, which are not located in its image under §4"
msgstr ""
"**Cantor**: ... So we are looking at a map §0 from §1 to the power set of "
"§2, and now the set of all those elements from §3 that are not in their "
"image under §4 ... \n"
"\n"
"Oh! An audience. No, *two* audiences! Hear and see, see and marvel.\n"
"\n"
"He pulls a piece of paper out of his top hat, folds it into a swallow, and "
"lets it fly down to you. \n"
"\n"
"**Cantor**: Given that I have two audiences, they might as well join in a "
"little, mightn’t they?"

#. §0: `suffices g : B`
#: Game.Levels.Spinoza.L04_ByContra
msgid "Provoce contradiction by using §0"
msgstr "**Scribble**: I would again use §0 to create a contradiction."

#: Game.Levels.Logo.L10_And
msgid "Intro Logo L10"
msgstr ""
"The next formalosopher in the queue has brought a question with him. He "
"presents it to us, sits down and starts knitting."

#. §0: `y : B`
#. §1: `x : A`
#. §2: `choose`
#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid ""
"Surjectivity states that each §0 possesses a preimage §1.\n"
"Try to construct a inverse mapping via §2"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: From surjectivity, you know that every §0 has a preimage §1. "
"Can't you use this to construct an inverse map with §2?"

#. §0: `«{h}»`
#: Game.Levels.Euklid.L02_prod_insert
msgid "Disect §0 into its constituents"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: And now let's break down assumption §0 into its three "
"components."

#. §0: `(hp : Prime p)`
#. §1: `p`
#. §2: `rw [prime_def] at hp`
#: Game.Levels.Prado.L06_Prime_Specialize__prime_def
msgid "§0 is the assumption that §1 is prime. Use §2"
msgstr ""
"**Scribble**: Here, §0 is of course the assumption that §1 is a prime "
"number. To work with this assumption, it is best to always apply §2."

#. §0: `push_neg`
#: Game.Levels.Mono.L03_NotInjective
msgid "Remind yourself of §0"
msgstr "**Scribble**: Do you remember §0?"

#. §0: `f a = f b`
#. §1: `g (f a) = g (f b)`
#. §2: `f a = f b`
#. §3: `rw`
#: Game.Levels.Iso.L02_Inverse
msgid ""
"Try to state that if §0 then also §1.\n"
"When §2 available use §3."
msgstr ""
"**You**: If the arguments §0 are the same, then also §1 – how do I formulate "
"this here? \n"
"\n"
"**Scribble**: Well, if you have §2, you can just use §3."

#. §0: `→`
#. §1: `↔`
#. §2: `intro`
#. §3: `revert`
#. §4: `intro`
#. §5: `apply`
#. §6: `apply at`
#. §7: `symm`
#. §8: `A ↔ B`
